content.text:
The syntax of `if`, `else if`, `else` statements is:
```javascript
if (condition) {
  // code to execute if condition is true
} else if (anotherCondition) {
  // code to execute if anotherCondition is true
} else {
  // code to execute if no conditions are true
}
```
- **Condition**: An expression that evaluates to `true` or `false`.
- **if**: Checks the first condition. If true, its block runs.
- **else if**: Checks additional conditions if the first is false.
- **else**: Runs if no conditions are true (optional).

content.code:
// Basic if example
const age = 18;
if (age >= 18) {
  console.log('You are an adult!');
}
// Output: You are an adult!

// if and else example
const temperature = 15;
if (temperature > 20) {
  console.log('It’s warm.');
} else {
  console.log('It’s cool.');
}
// Output: It’s cool.

// else if example
const score = 85;
if (score >= 90) {
  console.log('Grade: A');
} else if (score >= 80) {
  console.log('Grade: B');
} else if (score >= 70) {
  console.log('Grade: C');
} else {
  console.log('Grade: D or lower');
}
// Output: Grade: B

// else example
const day = 'Monday';
if (day === 'Saturday') {
  console.log('It’s a weekend!');
} else if (day === 'Sunday') {
  console.log('It’s a weekend!');
} else {
  console.log('It’s a weekday.');
}
// Output: It’s a weekday.

// Nested if example
const age = 16;
const hasPermission = true;
if (age >= 18) {
  console.log('You are an adult.');
} else {
  if (hasPermission) {
    console.log('You can enter with permission.');
  } else {
    console.log('You don’t have permission to enter.');
  }
}
// Output: You can enter with permission.

// Error-prone example
// Error: Incorrect condition
const temperature = 25;
if (temperature = 30) { // = is wrong, should be == or ===
  console.log('It’s warm.');
} else {
  console.log('It’s cool.');
}
// Output: It’s warm. (wrong, because temperature is set to 30)

// Correct approach
if (temperature === 30) {
  console.log('It’s warm.');
} else {
  console.log('It’s cool.');
}
// Output: It’s cool.

